			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I suppose since the Patriots are the Super Bowl champs, and the Red Sox are the World Series champs, lots of people from New England believe that they should be the ones to set national policies and determine the outcome of elections, and everyone who does not agree is stupid.
<br />
 Actually, to be fair, it is not just New Englanders, but also many living in large metropolitan areas. 
<br />
 I was in Washington, D.C. a few weeks ago for an expo, stayed at the Washington Hilton for a few days. I went down to the bar to have a few drinks. I was watching the TV sitting next to some guy, he was watching the CNN program, and he proclaimed "Bush is wrong on everything". I introduced myself to him and asked him why he would say that. He went on to say that his policies did not help any of the people who NEED help. I gave him my point of view that someone else's "need" should not give them a claim to an ounce of MY effort. 
<br />
 I then asked him what HE had ever done personally to help "needy" people out. Some drunk skank next to him piped in with "he has helped more people than YOU could ever dream of!" He proceeded to tell me that he was a doctor at a hospital that had to see people all the time who could not afford to pay their bills. And he also told me I was an "evil" person, I must be a republican.
<br />
 Of course, the discussion turned to health care. I started out by telling him that I hold doctors in very high esteem, with the education and hard work he had to go through in order to get his degreee and license. I also told him that if something were to happen to me that I needed a doctor's care, I would be happy to pay for it if I could afford it. If I could not afford it, I would not expect treatment for free on someone else's dime. 
<br />
 I explained to him that I am not an evil person, not a republican (lol), but simply someone who does not like to be held responsible for someone else's medical bills, whether they are hurt due to poor lifestyle choices/risks, or simply by an unavoidable accident. We went back and forth for a while about compassion etc. but I held my ground and he agreed with me on a lot of points. <span style="font-style: italic">I wonder how long it had been since someone had given this man credit for working in a difficult profession, rather than being envious of his position, or just wanting to USE his talents to make themselves feel better.</span> Something tells me he doesn't receive that type of praise very often. We ended up agreeing to disagree on some things, but parted friends and I was invited back the next evening for more discussion.
<br />
 
<br />
 Back to the main point. Why does it seem that people from up that way (New England, D.C., NYC) think they know what is best for the country as a whole? Maybe it is because they are closer in proximity to their European brethren than the rest of us? They are most certainly closer philisophically. I have to laugh when I see people from that area making posts here looking down their figurative noses on the rest of the U.S. with comments like "59 million stupid people" tee hee snort.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
